    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-03-28T09:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-03-28T09:00:00-05:00" n="201"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d201">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">851B.24/110: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General in Martinique</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Malige</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Fort-de-France</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-03-28T10:00:00-04:00"
                            >March 28, 1943—10 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 12:11 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>140. The High Commissioner protests in writing against first the requisitioning
                    of the <hi rend="italic">Guadeloupe</hi> and second the ship’s despatch to
                    French Guiana, of which he learns from Marquais and Gallantiere, respectively.
                    He terms the actions most unfriendly because violating the Gentlemen’s
                    Agreement, vexatious because aiding dissidents and harming the faithful, and
                    unworthy of “a great nation pretending to base its policy on the principles of
                    the Atlantic Charter”<note n="95" xml:id="d201fn95">Joint statement by President
                        Roosevelt and British Prime Minister Winston S. Churchill on August 14,
                        1941, <ref target="frus1941v01#pg_367">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1941, Vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, p. 367</ref>.</note> because tending to
                    induce revolt by starvation. He makes all reservations as to political and
                    litigious consequences and does not recognize that “your Government, as long as
                    you represent it here, should inform me of its decisions through an ordinary
                    propaganda service”.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Malige</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
